2019-12-21 05:28:37	Araq	the type of 'recover block' is 'owned ref', only 'owned ref' can be passed to a thread/channel
2019-12-21 05:29:05	Araq	'owned ref' can also be used elsewhere and it enforces moves just like in the B/D design
2019-12-21 05:30:13	Araq	so if you have a singly linked list with 'owned refs' inside, you can pass head/rest to different threads
2019-12-21 05:30:50	Araq	if you don't then 'recover' is also unlikely to help you
2019-12-21 05:31:07	Araq	but that's ok, lists etc need to be prepared for threading
2019-12-21 05:33:49	clyybber	,Exactly
2019-12-21 05:34:00	Araq	this means we lack B/D's "dangling ref" error state since we use refcounting, we can keep the refcounting thread local since we "move" stuff to threads and it's memory safe
2019-12-21 05:34:16	clyybber	Yes
2019-12-21 05:36:30	clyybber	I'm currently investigating wether this recover block can be made implicit. So rather than have a block we trace the orgins of `someRef` in `let b = own someRef`.
2019-12-21 05:36:44	clyybber	And during that I have stumbled upon a few insights
2019-12-21 05:37:18	clyybber	Inside a recover block there does not need to be refcounting
2019-12-21 05:37:45	clyybber	And I'm talking about unowned refs
2019-12-21 05:38:02	Araq	sounds wrong to me
2019-12-21 05:39:47	clyybber	think about it. As long as you don't let the refs inside of that block escape (which you cant with a recover block) the result of that block is an owned ref. Since they can't escape the block they need not be refcounted
2019-12-21 05:40:01	clyybber	The one ref that survives will be taken ownership off in the resulting owned ref
2019-12-21 05:40:43	clyybber	So all other ones except of that one can be destroyed
2019-12-21 05:41:39	Araq	var x = foo(); if complexCondition: x = bar()
2019-12-21 05:41:55	Araq	^ better destroy the old x in the 2nd assignment
2019-12-21 05:42:16	Araq	yes, you can avoid the RC ops but the basic machinery can't be avoided
2019-12-21 05:43:22	clyybber	Yeah
2019-12-21 05:43:35	clyybber	But eliding RC ops seems really useful
2019-12-21 05:45:03	clyybber	This insight can be extended as follows: Only ref assignments from or to fields of outer vars, outer vars, or globals need to do RC ops
2019-12-21 05:45:41	clyybber	where outer vars are outside of the scope that an unowned ref is introduced in
2019-12-21 05:46:47	clyybber	Now the tricky part is constructing some flow based rules out of that insight, so that we don't have to `block:` everythign
2019-12-21 05:47:00	<--	ecker (~ecker@x5f70c3b9.dyn.telefonica.de) has quit (Quit: Leaving)
2019-12-21 05:49:43	Araq	we also elide rc ops via 'sink' and 'lent'
2019-12-21 05:50:22	clyybber	Yeah, combining all these elision methods, I think we can get the RC ops overhead really low
2019-12-21 05:50:56	clyybber	And that way cycle checking also gets rarer
2019-12-21 05:51:25	Araq	cycle checking lost
2019-12-21 05:51:43	Araq	it is buggy and **slow**
2019-12-21 05:52:23	Araq	the only way to make it not slow is via delaying the cycle checking
2019-12-21 05:52:33	clyybber	Or via not doing rc ops?
2019-12-21 05:52:43	Araq	and then you enter non-predictable MM
2019-12-21 05:52:53	Araq	which is what we want to get away from
2019-12-21 05:54:15	FromGitter	<Willyboar> @xmonader don't worry just joking
2019-12-21 05:54:23	Araq	doing it via RC ops is ok but the condition rc > 1 is not good enough
2019-12-21 05:54:40	Araq	it triggers too often
2019-12-21 05:54:59	Araq	Python uses a generational algorithm
2019-12-21 05:55:25	clyybber	Yeah, though I think with the above approach we can get it at least a bit lower. Since none of the unowned refs in a rcover block/data flow need to be cycle checked
2019-12-21 05:55:42	clyybber	And then maybe we stumble upon another bunch of optimizations
2019-12-21 05:56:53	Araq	but systems programming is not about "optimizations we hope work out and affect O(n) behaviour"
2019-12-21 05:57:46	clyybber	Sure
2019-12-21 05:57:47	Araq	the critical part here is the algorithmic complexity that is affected
2019-12-21 05:58:23	Araq	once the cycle collector doesn't cause crashes anymore, we can give programmers a 'markAsCyclic' proc they need to call for cycle collection
2019-12-21 05:58:32	Araq	then the cost is exposed
